It is enveloped in very fine skins in entirely separate layers, and then consists of several kernels in a cluster‚ each of these also having a coat of its own3 it has a pungent flavour, and the more kernels there were the more pungent it is. Garlic as well as onions gives an offensive smel] to the breath, though when boiled it causes no smell. The difference between the various kinds consists in the time they take to ripen—the early kind ripens in 60 days—and also in their size. Ulpicum also comes in this class, the plant called by the Greeks Cyprian garlic‚ or by others antis- corodon; it holds a high rank among the dishes of the country people, particularly in Africa, and it is larger than garlic; when beaten up in oil and vinegar it swells up in foam to a surprising size. Some people say that ulpicum and garlic must not be planted in level ground, and advise placing it in little mounds a yard apart like a chain of forts; there must be a space of four inches between the grains, and as soon as three leaves have broken out the plants must be hoed over: they grow largcr the ostener they are hoed.
